#Steps to install SASS
🧱 1. Make sure Node.js and npm are installed

Check your versions:

node -v
npm -v


If you get version numbers (like v20.x or 11.x), you’re good.
If not → download and install from https://nodejs.org

📂 2. Go to your project folder

Navigate into your project (for example, your Airbnb project):

cd C:\Users\Aloice\Desktop\Airbnb

📦 3. Initialize npm (if you haven’t yet)

This creates a package.json file that tracks dependencies:

npm init -y

🪄 4. Install Sass (the modern Dart Sass)

Run:

npm install sass --save-dev


🧠 What this does:

Installs the latest version of Dart Sass.

Adds it as a dev dependency in your package.json.

⚙️ 5. Check if Sass installed correctly

Run:

npx sass --version


If you see something like:

1.80.0 compiled with dart2js


Boom 💥 — Sass is ready to roll.

🎨 6. Create your Sass files

Inside your project, create a folder structure like this:

project/
├─ src/
│   └─ styles.scss
└─ dist/
    └─ styles.css


In styles.scss, add something simple to test:

$main-color: #e63946;

body {
  background: $main-color;
  color: white;
}

🧩 7. Compile Sass to CSS

Now compile it manually:

npx sass src/styles.scss dist/styles.css


Or keep it watching for changes:

npx sass src/styles.scss dist/styles.css --watch


Every time you save styles.scss, Sass will recompile automatically.

🪞 8. Link the compiled CSS in your HTML

In your <head> tag:

<link rel="stylesheet" href="dist/styles.css">


✅ That’s it!
You’ve installed Sass, configured it, and set up automatic compilation.
